also why is my maximum data points not working?
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Request Count Graph</title>
    <script src="https://code.highcharts.com/highcharts.js"></script>
</head>
<body>

<div id="requestCountGraph" style="width: 100%; height: 400px;"></div>

<script>
    var requestData = [];
    var lastRequestCount = null;
    var maxDataPoints = 20; // Modify as needed for max length of the graph

    // Create the Highcharts graph
    var chart = Highcharts.chart('requestCountGraph', {
        chart: {
            type: 'line',
            events: {
                load: requestDataUpdate
            }
        },
        title: {
            text: 'L7 DSTAT ~ http://127.0.0.1:5000/hit'
        },
        xAxis: {
            type: 'datetime',
            tickPixelInterval: 150
        },
        yAxis: {
            title: {
                text: 'Request Count Difference'
            }
        },
        series: [{
            name: 'Requests',
            data: []
        }]
    });

    function requestDataUpdate() {
        setInterval(function() {
            fetch('http://127.0.0.1:5000/api/dstat')
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                var currentRequestCount = data.total_requests;
                if (lastRequestCount !== null) {  // Skip first request
                    var diff = currentRequestCount - lastRequestCount;
                    var x = (new Date()).getTime();  // current time

                    // Add the point to the graph
                    chart.series[0].addPoint([x, diff], true, requestData.length > maxDataPoints);

                    // Store request data (optional)
                    requestData.push(diff);

                    // Keep array size under maxDataPoints
                    if (requestData.length > maxDataPoints) {
                        requestData.shift();
                    }
                }
                lastRequestCount = currentRequestCount;
            });
        }, 1000); // Update every second
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>

The issue with the maximum data points not working properly seems to be related to the condition provided to the `addPoint` method. The `addPoint` method of the Highcharts series object takes three arguments:

1. The point or an array with [x, y] values.
2. Whether the chart should be redrawn after the point is added.
3. Whether to shift the data series by removing the first point (when the series has reached a specific number of points).

Your current condition for shifting the graph is based on the `requestData` array length, but you should be checking the series data length instead. The `requestData` array is not necessary for the chart to function since Highcharts manages the data internally within the series. You're adding points directly to the chart series and should shift based on the length of the chart series data.

Here's how you can correct the code:

```javascript
function requestDataUpdate() {
    setInterval(function() {
        fetch('http://127.0.0.1:5000/api/dstat')
        .then(response => response.json())
        .then(data => {
            var currentRequestCount = data.total_requests;
            if (lastRequestCount !== null) {  // Skip first request
                var diff = currentRequestCount - lastRequestCount;
                var x = (new Date()).getTime();  // current time

                // Add the point to the graph
                // and shift the series if necessary
                var shift = chart.series[0].data.length >= maxDataPoints;
                chart.series[0].addPoint([x, diff], true, shift);

                // No need to use requestData array as Highcharts manages the data
            }
            lastRequestCount = currentRequestCount;
        });
    }, 1000); // Update every second
}
```

By using the `chart.series[0].data.length` check instead of `requestData.length`, you make sure you're using the actual length of the data series in the chart to decide if the graph should shift.

Also, I removed `requestData`, as it is not necessary. Highcharts is handling the series data internally, so there is no need to maintain a separate array of data points for the graph. If you're not using `requestData` for any other purpose, it can be discarded.

Implement the updated function and test it to see if the graph now correctly maintains a maximum of 20 data points.

To style the Highcharts chart, you can modify the chart options in the Highcharts chart configuration object. For the specific requirements you've mentioned (no background and a filled line chart), you will need to adjust the `chart.backgroundColor` and the `plotOptions` with `fillColor` for the series:

```javascript
var chart = Highcharts.chart('requestCountGraph', {
    chart: {
        type: 'line',
        backgroundColor: null, // Set background to transparent
        events: {
            load: requestDataUpdate
        }
    },
    title: {
        text: 'L7 DSTAT ~ http://127.0.0.1:5000/hit'
    },
    xAxis: {
        type: 'datetime',
        tickPixelInterval: 150
    },
    yAxis: {
        title: {
            text: 'Request Count Difference'
        }
    },
    plotOptions: {
        line: {
            lineWidth: 3, // You can adjust the line thickness
            marker: {
                enabled: false // Disable markers for a cleaner line
            },
            fillColor: {
                linearGradient: [0, 0, 0, 300], // Gradient fill direction
                stops: [
                    [0, Highcharts.getOptions().colors[0]], // Top color
                    [1, Highcharts.Color(Highcharts.getOptions().colors[0]).setOpacity(0).get('rgba')] // Bottom, transparent
                ]
            }
        },
        series: {
            fillOpacity: 0.1 // Semi-transparent fill
        }
    },
    series: [{
        name: 'Requests',
        data: [],
        lineWidth: 1, // Optional: Line thickness
        color: '#FF0000', // Optional: Line color
        fillColor: { // Optional: Gradient fill
            linearGradient: {x1: 0, y1: 0, x2: 0, y2: 1},
            stops: [
                [0, Highcharts.Color('#FF0000').setOpacity(0.5).get('rgba')], // Top, colored
                [1, Highcharts.Color('#FF0000').setOpacity(0).get('rgba')] // Bottom, transparent
            ]
        }
    }]
});
```

Here's a breakdown of the changes:

- `backgroundColor: null` is used within the `chart` configuration to set the chart's background to be transparent.
- `plotOptions.line.fillColor` specifies a gradient fill for the line series. The gradient is defined with the `linearGradient` property and a set of color stops that designate the fill color at different points in the gradient.
- The `stops` array inside `fillColor` contains tuples with two elements: the first element is the position at which the color stop is placed (ranging from 0 to 1), and the second element is the color at that stop. You can set the starting color and fade it to transparency towards the bottom of the line.
- `fillOpacity` under `plotOptions.series` sets the opacity for the series fill color.

Remember, the `fillColor` uses the first color from the default Highcharts color array, but you can define any color you want in `rgba` format. Adjust the line `color`, `lineWidth`, and gradient `stops` to style the series according to your design preferences.

Make sure to include the `Highcharts.Color` utility to facilitate color manipulation if you wish to use semi-opacity or gradients (It's typically included with the Highcharts library).
